AGI - George Glezmann>, a U.S. citizen for more than two years in Afghanistan, was released by the Taliban and is already traveling to the United States.> A source told CNN. Glezmann, 66 years old, was released after weeks of negotiations conducted by mediators of Qatar> and the United States. The US envoy Adam Boehler was also in close contact with his counterparts in Qatar to ensure the release of Glezmann. The spokesman of the Afghan Ministry of Foreign Affairs released the photographs of Boehler and former U.S. Ambassador to Afghanistan Zalmay Khalilzad during the meeting with Taliban officials.
Khalilzad confirmed Glezmann's release on X stating: "Today is a good day. We managed to get the release of an American citizen after two years of detention in Kabul."
<div </div
"The Taliban government has agreed to release him as a gesture of good will towards the President of the United States and the American people. George is coming home to his family," he added. Glezmann was arrested by the Taliban in December 2022, about 16 months after the group regained control of Afghanistan, and was declared unjustly held by the United States in September 2023.
According to US senators Jon Ossoff >e Raphael Warnock> - who campaigned for the release of Glezmann - traveled to Afghanistan for a five-day trip "to explore the cultural landscape and the rich history of the country". The two last July claimed that Glezmann was held in "a nine-foot cell for nine feet with other prisoners." Until July 2024, Glezmann had not been granted consular visits by U.S. officials and had "only seven phone calls per month for a total of 54 minutes exclusively with his family", the senators stressed.
&nbsp;
<div </div
The United States has no diplomatic presence in Afghanistan, having closed their embassy after the Taliban took power in August 2022. Qatar is currently representing the United States in Kabul, acting as their "protective power". Glezmann is the third U.S. citizen to be freed from Afghanistan this year, after Ryan Corbett> and William McKenty>, released both in an exchange of prisoners in January. The agreement to free Corbett and McKenty was reached in the last hours of the mandate of former President Joe Biden>, after the Taliban agreed to exchange them with Khan Mohammed>, a member of the Taliban who was serving a sentence to life sentence for narcoterrorism in an American prison.
This agreement was also facilitated by Qatar, which hosted several rounds of negotiations between the United States and the Taliban, also providing logistical support to operations to get the pair out of Kabul. U.S. officials wanted Glezmann and another American in Afghanistan, Mahmoud Habi> to be part of the agreement, and expressed disappointment at the time because the two were not delivered in January. However, they said they could not refuse the offer at least for Corbett and McKenty.
The Taliban never admitted to holding Habibi, but the United States still considers it a hostage. Glezmann's wife, Aleksandra, said last July, with a letter to Biden, that her husband's health was getting worse. This morning in Kabul, the Taliban Foreign Minister, Amir Khan Muttaqi>, met with U.S. officials, including Boehler, in turn accompanied by former Washington envoy in Afghanistan, Khalilzad.&nbsp;
